      "markdown": "Matrix Form of the Linear System (1).\n\nFrom the definition of matrix multiplication we see that the m equations of (1) may l bev written as a single vector equation \n\n\n\n(2)\n\n$$\\mathbf{A}\\mathbf{x}=\\mathbf{b}$$\n\nwhere the coefficient matrix $\\mathbf{A}=[a_{j k}]$ is the m ×n matrix \n\n$$\\mathbf{A}=\\left[\\begin{matrix}{a_{_{11}}}&{a_{_{12}}}&{\\cdots}&{a_{_{1n}}}\\\\ {a_{_{21}}}&{a_{_{22}}}&{\\cdots}&{a_{_{2n}}}\\\\ {\\cdot}&{\\cdot}&{\\cdots}&{\\cdot}\\\\ {a_{_{m1}}}&{a_{_{m2}}}&{\\cdots}&{a_{_{m n}}}\\\\ \\end{matrix}\\right],\\quad\\mathrm{~a n d~}\\quad\\mathbf{x}=\\left[\\begin{matrix}{x_{_{1}}}\\\\ {\\cdot}\\\\ {\\cdot}\\\\ {\\cdot}\\\\ {x_{_{n}}}\\\\ \\end{matrix}\\right]\\quad\\mathrm{~a n d~}\\quad\\mathbf{b}=\\left[\\begin{matrix}{b_{_{1}}}\\\\ {\\vdots}\\\\ {b_{_{m}}}\\\\ \\end{matrix}\\right]$$\n\nare column vectors.\n\nSection 7.3 p34\n\nAdvanced Engineering Mathematics, 10/e by Edwin Kreyszig Copyright 2011 by John Wiley & Sons. All rights reserved.",
